00:53:45.750 --> 00:53:46.516
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:53:46.516 --> 00:53:48.056
So I've been using Scrum a bit.

00:53:48.056 --> 00:53:49.180
And I've really enjoyed it.

00:53:49.180 --> 00:53:55.640
And my question was about the
burndown for one-week sprints.

00:53:55.640 --> 00:53:57.120
What's the value of that?

00:53:57.120 --> 00:53:59.480
Because it was the
Schwaber 30 Days,

00:53:59.480 --> 00:54:01.400
you could get some
kind of trajectory.

00:54:01.400 --> 00:54:03.840
But when you only
have five days,

00:54:03.840 --> 00:54:05.640
it's very hard to
correct something

00:54:05.640 --> 00:54:08.610
that's gone out of when you've
only had two or three days.

00:54:08.610 --> 00:54:10.965
There's not a lot of
opportunity to change.

00:54:10.965 --> 00:54:12.590
DR. JEFF SUTHERLAND:
That's what people

00:54:12.590 --> 00:54:14.690
say when they're
starting off with Scrum.

00:54:14.690 --> 00:54:19.460
But in my company, we run our
company completely by Scrum.

00:54:19.460 --> 00:54:20.860
We run all in one-week sprints.

00:54:23.550 --> 00:54:25.920
We use some tooling
because we have

00:54:25.920 --> 00:54:27.890
a lot of distributed people.

00:54:27.890 --> 00:54:30.060
It has a burnup
instead of a burndown.

00:54:30.060 --> 00:54:31.905
But it gives us quite
a good visualization

00:54:31.905 --> 00:54:34.280
of what's going on.

00:54:34.280 --> 00:54:36.610
But for a lot of
companies today,

00:54:36.610 --> 00:54:38.559
particularly Google
in Mountain View,

00:54:38.559 --> 00:54:40.100
I don't know how
you're working here.

00:54:40.100 --> 00:54:42.520
You're in a continuous
delivery mode.

00:54:42.520 --> 00:54:45.960
So you figure out how much you
deliver this week-- burning it

00:54:45.960 --> 00:54:47.402
up.

00:54:47.402 --> 00:54:48.360
Is that happening here?

00:54:48.360 --> 00:54:51.070
Are you guys delivery stuff
every day to production?

00:54:51.070 --> 00:54:52.330
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:54:52.330 --> 00:54:54.360
DR. JEFF SUTHERLAND: Yeah.

00:54:54.360 --> 00:54:57.670
So you just burnup for a week.

00:54:57.670 --> 00:55:01.040
Most companies today don't
use four-week sprints anymore.

00:55:01.040 --> 00:55:02.960
I mean, Ken still likes 30 days.

00:55:02.960 --> 00:55:07.602
But probably 70% of Scrums
today have two weeks.

00:55:07.602 --> 00:55:09.510
A few three weeks.

00:55:09.510 --> 00:55:10.530
A few, one week.

00:55:13.700 --> 00:55:16.260
We find that one-week
sprints are more intense.

00:55:16.260 --> 00:55:19.710
So you have to have a
team that wants to really

00:55:19.710 --> 00:55:21.540
be focused and disciplined.

00:55:21.540 --> 00:55:25.240
And if you do that on the weekly
cycle, you get more learning.

00:55:25.240 --> 00:55:30.900
It's really the learning cycle
that propels the product.

00:55:33.345 --> 00:55:33.886
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:55:33.886 --> 00:55:35.677
I've worked at a couple
