00:55:36.900 --> 00:55:39.480
And there seems to quite a
vastly different interpretation

00:55:39.480 --> 00:55:41.694
from company to company.

00:55:41.694 --> 00:55:43.360
Was that kind of the
intention of Scrum?

00:55:43.360 --> 00:55:45.360
Were you leaving it very
open to interpretation?

00:55:45.360 --> 00:55:46.960
Or do you find
that Scrum is kind

00:55:46.960 --> 00:55:49.130
of misrepresented
by some companies?

00:55:49.130 --> 00:55:53.400
Well, the Scrum Guide,
we try to keep minimal,

00:55:53.400 --> 00:55:56.010
the middle framework.

00:55:56.010 --> 00:56:00.751
But the misinterpretations
that we see are really extreme.

00:56:00.751 --> 00:56:02.500
About half of the Scrum
teams in the world

00:56:02.500 --> 00:56:04.470
can't deliver anything.

00:56:04.470 --> 00:56:07.265
And so they're not
doing it the way Ken

00:56:07.265 --> 00:56:09.920
and I are talking about.

00:56:09.920 --> 00:56:13.520
We have Scrum teams that
are spending a year doing

00:56:13.520 --> 00:56:17.920
two-week sprints for
requirements for six months.

00:56:17.920 --> 00:56:19.520
And then, two-week
sprints for coding

00:56:19.520 --> 00:56:23.212
with no testing
for three months.

00:56:23.212 --> 00:56:24.420
And then, they're never done.

00:56:24.420 --> 00:56:26.844
So the project's always
late by this time.

00:56:26.844 --> 00:56:28.010
And they think that's Scrum.

00:56:28.010 --> 00:56:32.566
So people totally misinterpret
what we're talking about.

00:56:32.566 --> 00:56:36.100
Yeah, it's nothing we can do
about that other than-- it

00:56:36.100 --> 00:56:37.796
makes for a lot of
coaching business.

00:56:37.796 --> 00:56:38.420
It's a lot of--

00:56:38.420 --> 00:56:39.290
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:39.290 --> 00:56:41.470
Scrum coaches out there
that have good jobs.

00:56:41.470 --> 00:56:44.689
[CHUCKLES]

00:56:44.689 --> 00:56:46.480
YVONNE: We have time
