00:56:58.033 --> 00:56:58.692
[LAUGHTER]

00:56:58.692 --> 00:57:00.650
--or for those of us who
are just new to Scrum,

00:57:00.650 --> 00:57:04.140
could you maybe
just go into what

00:57:04.140 --> 00:57:06.112
that recipe is to
make the secret sauce?

00:57:06.112 --> 00:57:07.820
I mean, just really
just bang through it.

00:57:07.820 --> 00:57:11.213
You'd said the BootStrapping, if
you'd just describe that to us.

00:57:11.213 --> 00:57:12.212
DR. JEFF SUTHERLAND: OK.

00:57:12.212 --> 00:57:14.200
the BootStrap is
the Scrum Guide.

00:57:14.200 --> 00:57:17.000
And often, people say why
do we have to do this?

00:57:17.000 --> 00:57:21.150
You need a list of stuff to
do that's in a ready state.

00:57:21.150 --> 00:57:24.590
That means it's immediately
actionable and it's small.

00:57:24.590 --> 00:57:27.620
So you have to do
whatever needs to be

00:57:27.620 --> 00:57:30.870
done before you enter
into that sprint.

00:57:30.870 --> 00:57:33.460
If that's not clear,
then you have a mess.

00:57:33.460 --> 00:57:36.080
OK, so that's the first secret.

00:57:36.080 --> 00:57:39.100
The second secret is when
you start into that sprint,

00:57:39.100 --> 00:57:41.550
you want to take just
enough, and not too much,

00:57:41.550 --> 00:57:45.620
so that you can cleanly
complete it in the sprint.

00:57:45.620 --> 00:57:47.230
The reason being
we have discovered,

00:57:47.230 --> 00:57:48.688
I work for a venture
capital group.

00:57:48.688 --> 00:57:51.550
And after running
thousands of sprints,

00:57:51.550 --> 00:57:55.050
we have found that teams
that finish the sprint early,

00:57:55.050 --> 00:57:58.750
with everything down and
working, accelerate faster.

00:57:58.750 --> 00:58:01.530
So the kind of improvement
that we're looking for

00:58:01.530 --> 00:58:05.260
requires you to cleanly
finish and, in your case,

00:58:05.260 --> 00:58:08.060
you should be able to deploy
in whatever sprint [? likes ?]

00:58:08.060 --> 00:58:09.087
you're having.

00:58:09.087 --> 00:58:10.670
So you don't want
to take too much in.

00:58:10.670 --> 00:58:13.770
So that sprint planning,
It can be one minute.

00:58:13.770 --> 00:58:16.630
But you need to make a decision
to take the right things in

00:58:16.630 --> 00:58:18.227
and not too much.

00:58:18.227 --> 00:58:20.560
AUDIENCE: Well, when you're
talking about one week, that

00:58:20.560 --> 00:58:23.684
almost sounds like a Gantt
chart style planning.

00:58:23.684 --> 00:58:26.100
So, really, the one week is
kind of like a rough estimate.

00:58:26.100 --> 00:58:28.890
If this is how much work we
should get done in one week,

00:58:28.890 --> 00:58:30.172
and now it's like, let's
just burn through it.

00:58:30.172 --> 00:58:32.130
Or are you really looking
at one week and then,

00:58:32.130 --> 00:58:33.952
either coming in early or late?

00:58:33.952 --> 00:58:34.952
DR. JEFF SUTHERLAND: No.

00:58:38.610 --> 00:58:41.950
This is a long discussion
about planning.

00:58:41.950 --> 00:58:44.870
But for a lot of
things in Google,

00:58:44.870 --> 00:58:46.860
you don't care when
it comes out, right?

00:58:46.860 --> 00:58:48.740
It comes out when it comes out.

00:58:48.740 --> 00:58:51.759
But for some projects,
people need to plan.

00:58:51.759 --> 00:58:52.800
And they need to predict.

00:58:52.800 --> 00:58:55.470
And the product owner needs
to be able to give dates.

00:58:55.470 --> 00:58:56.840
This happened in AdWords.

00:58:56.840 --> 00:58:59.830
That's why they implemented
Scrum in AdWords many years

00:58:59.830 --> 00:59:00.770
ago.

00:59:00.770 --> 00:59:03.070
Because they need to
be more predictable.

00:59:03.070 --> 00:59:06.010
There were millions of
people using AdWords.

00:59:06.010 --> 00:59:07.820
So in order to get
that, the product owner

00:59:07.820 --> 00:59:10.050
needs to know a
velocity of production.

00:59:10.050 --> 00:59:13.680
And he gets that off
the sprint cycle.

00:59:13.680 --> 00:59:16.800
Also, we find that people
that cleanly finish work,

00:59:16.800 --> 00:59:19.560
in a cycle, need to take
the right amount in.

00:59:19.560 --> 00:59:22.990
So knowing what they can
do is important to get

00:59:22.990 --> 00:59:27.090
in this rhythm of
a planning cycle.

00:59:27.090 --> 00:59:29.640
People often think, well we can
just do one thing at a time.

00:59:29.640 --> 00:59:32.540
We'll just do one thing at a
time and don't worry about it.

00:59:32.540 --> 00:59:34.079
Those teams don't go as fast.

00:59:34.079 --> 00:59:35.620
People had said,
OK, this week, we're

00:59:35.620 --> 00:59:36.750
going to get this stuff done.

00:59:36.750 --> 00:59:37.130
Bang.

00:59:37.130 --> 00:59:37.530
And they get it done.

00:59:37.530 --> 00:59:38.840
Then next week, we're
going to get more done.

00:59:38.840 --> 00:59:40.480
Bang, and they get that done.

00:59:40.480 --> 00:59:42.390
Those teams really accelerate.

00:59:42.390 --> 00:59:46.260
It's like winning soccer game.

00:59:46.260 --> 00:59:47.542
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:59:47.542 --> 00:59:48.750
I'm just going to keep going.

00:59:48.750 --> 00:59:50.972
So kind of like your
punctuated equilibrium thing.

00:59:50.972 --> 00:59:52.680
So when you're looking
at this, it really

00:59:52.680 --> 00:59:53.940
should be a small
change that you

00:59:53.940 --> 00:59:55.476
can do in one week,
which is setting you off

00:59:55.476 --> 00:59:56.165
in the right direction.

00:59:56.165 --> 00:59:56.420
DR. JEFF SUTHERLAND:
That's right.

00:59:56.420 --> 00:59:58.926
AUDIENCE: No change should
take more than the sprint.

